    # [Scene: Abandoned Promenade | Dusk]

    scene bg ch15_228644_1 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Low, patient water against pilings; a gull calls and dies off]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Sparse cello and distant, slow percussion—tide rhythm]
    "You walk the promenade with the compass heavy in your palm. The brass is cool where your fingers press the dent beside the hinge; it feels like a small, stubborn truth. The legal notice from the"
    "night before sits in the back of your mind like a knot—formal words that can be threaded into law or into leverage—but it doesn't change the wet weight of the world under your boots."
    "Salt smells sharp, mixed with the faint oil of an old generator and the sweetness of seaweed warmed by a late sun. Puddles mirror the sky in split images; the tide's mark has become a mural"
    "of names and dates and sharp declarations of who remembers what used to be here. A child's spray-paint heart is half-obscured by a band of builder's tape; a broken carousel horse has been claimed by algae"
    "and a braid of warning flags."
    "You note the small things—the way the wind tugs the scarf at your throat, the way light slants off exposed nails—and all of it records itself into your chest like data. You have been cataloging losses"
    "and their correlates for months: roofs, fish runs, trust. You have also cataloged the stitches: the garden behind the market, the makeshift co-ops, the dozen people who learned how to read a tide line because you"
    "taught them. The list of what you owe is long, and it is not only measured in material terms."
    "From somewhere ahead there is a silhouette at the rail—familiar enough that your muscles loosen, cautious enough that your mouth rehearses a thousand things. Whether he's come by for a morning, for a year, or appears"
    "only in certain memories, the presence is patchwork: threadbare in places, whole in others. You do not demand clarity. You are practiced now in making room for partial truths."
    show jonah_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "You always find the old places first."
    "(His voice is grounded like knotted rope; whether he's turned toward you or only in the memory of him is a detail you don't pin down.)"
    show maya_armitage at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_armitage "They're stubborn. Like everything that's still here."
    "(You don't ask what 'here' means—it's bigger than any single shore.)"

    jonah_reyes "Stubborn's good. Gets things through a winter."
    "(There is an unreadable softness at the edges of his tone—a man who can still joke and still hold a not-quite-silent grief.)"

    maya_armitage "Sometimes it feels like stubbornness and stubbornness alone won't be enough."
    "(You look out at the water. Your words mean the legal fights, the money wrung into clauses, the people who couldn't be saved by good plans alone.)"

    jonah_reyes "No. It won't. But it's what we have."
    "(He folds into a quiet that is more complicated than support and more tender than promise.)"
    "There are things both of you say without speaking: the name of the brother who didn't come home, the pile of grant applications, the nights of strategy that stole sleep from you both. You trade fragments—comfort, complaint, practical updates—three turns of speech that braid like rope: anchor, strain, and hold."

    menu:
        "Run your thumb along the tide line, tracing names":
            "Your thumb smudges damp paint; a name blurs and becomes less like a loss and more like a ledger you keep by touch."
        "Take out your notebook and photograph the line":
            "The picture flattens and files itself; later it will be evidence, testimony—safely detachable from the salt."
        "Kneel and pick up the driftwood horse":
            "The wood is rough and damp; you press it to your chest and feel its history—childhood, abandonment, reclamation—stacked in a single grain."

    # --- merge ---
    "The promenade responds and the main narrative continues."
    "You choose in a small, private way and the promenade responds with the same ancient impartiality. Choices settle into the drift. The sky deepens toward indigo and the town's string lights blink on, one by one, cautious as migratory birds."
    # [Scene: Community Garden | Morning]
    hide jonah_reyes
    hide maya_armitage

    scene bg ch15_228644_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Bees at work; Nan's low, hearty laugh]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A soft piano motif, minor but warm]
    "The garden has shrunk since you were a kid—less acreage, more love. Nan moves between beds with slow authority, her cardigan's elbow a patchwork map of repairs. The scent of citrus and damp earth is immediate"
    "and domestic; this is the work of people who have learned that tending is a way of remembering."
    show gracie_nan_armitage at left:
        zoom 0.7

    gracie_nan_armitage "You look like you carried the sea inside you all night."
    "(She squints at you, then laughs, the sound like a buoy bumping a dock.)"
    show maya_armitage at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_armitage "It's been filing years."
    "(You grin, but the gravity under the joke is real. You set the compass on a flat stone and watch the needle wobble slightly as if it, too, remembers storms.)"

    gracie_nan_armitage "I'm not saying let it drown you. I'm saying learn when to bail and when to steady the lines."
    "(She pats a small sprout with the back of her hand as if greeting an old friend.)"

    maya_armitage "I don't know the math of that yet."
    "(There's the confession: a scientist made of lists who still cannot compute the cost of a life.)"

    gracie_nan_armitage "No one does. We learn it by making choices. Sometimes we lose something we love. Sometimes we gain a garden. Both are true."
    "(She looks toward the market's rooftop where a few young hands bend over a rain cistern; pride softens the hard edge of her voice.)"
    "There is a back-and-forth that is more than exchange—it's inheritance. Nan presses a basil leaf into your palm: oil and citrus and a memory."

    maya_armitage "Promise me something."
    "(You find yourself asking for a pact not written in ink but in bread and soil.)"

    gracie_nan_armitage "Promise?"
    "(She feigns offense, then realises you are serious.)"

    maya_armitage "Promise you'll keep telling the kids about the old harbor, even if they never fish from it. Promise you'll teach them how to read tide lines and how to keep a bowl of soup hot when the power goes out."
    "(The list is small and enormous.)"

    gracie_nan_armitage "I promise. And you—you promise yourself sleep once in a while."
    "(She smacks you lightly on the shoulder, more admonishment than threat.)"

    menu:
        "Agree to sleep more":
            "You laugh and say you will try; it tastes like compromise and feels like thin relief."
        "Tell her you can't afford to rest yet":
            "You say the words and they sit heavy; Nan's face folds in worry and pride at the same time."

    # --- merge ---
    "Nan watches you and the main narrative continues."
    "Nan watches you choose to be both fragile and steady. Her laugh comes out like a small bell. The garden is a ledger of small recoveries; it is enough in its way."
    # [Scene: The Tidal Institute (Field Lab) | Afternoon]
    hide gracie_nan_armitage
    hide maya_armitage

    scene bg ch15_228644_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The murmur of a dozen voices; the click of a bracelet logging data]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low strings, a single, sustained note that slows in tempo]
    "The lab is quieter than it used to be—equipment mothballed, projects in frames drying on racks—but alive with fragments of persistence. A kid presses a tide-line mark into a notebook while you show them how the"
    "microclimate bracelet blinks with a soft blue. Rafi passes by with paint on his knuckles and a grin that admits there is still mischief in engineering."
    show rafi_chen at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rafi_chen "We wired the community cistern to the citizen sensors. You should see the uptime."
    "(He holds up a tablet; uptime numbers bloom green across the screen.)"
    show maya_armitage at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_armitage "Good. Something that keeps itself alive without asking for letters and signatures."
    "(Relief is small and technical and it tastes like solder and rain.)"

    rafi_chen "Don't write the funding body a love letter in your sleep."
    "(He nudges you, then softens.) 'They're playing chess, Maya. We're playing go—lots of stones laid across many turns.'"

    maya_armitage "Maybe that's what's needed."
    "(You think about systemic problems and systemic sacrifice. You think about the legal scaffolding you helped build, the injunctions, the hours spent turning the truth into law.)"
    "A small group of townsfolk filter in: a woman with a child, an older fisher who nods at the tank of shellfish, two teens who once lived on the promenade and now help run water checks."
    "People bring small offerings—cornmeal, a jar of preserved lemons, a list of complaints and gratitude folded together."

    "Townsperson" "How do we explain to kids that some places won't be for sleeping anymore?"
    "(Her voice cracks; you know the question is both practical and moral.)"

    maya_armitage "We teach them the language of loss,' you say. 'But we also teach them how to make a new kind of living."
    "(You think of watches wound tight—some will break and some will find new springs.)"
    "There is a tension held like a taut rope: policy and care, legal muscle and neighborhood kindness. The Tidal Institute hums as a small, persistent heart in the town's chest."
    "Jonah Reyes's presence here is faint as sea-glass—maybe a visit, maybe an ongoing thing, maybe a memory stitched into the edges of the room. He moves through the lab in fragments like a chorus of support, never dissolving the ache that both of you carry."
    show jonah_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "You think the kids will want to stay here?"
    "(He asks, voice quiet and direct, asking the practical question that hides the personal stakes.)"

    maya_armitage "Some will. Some won't. Our job is to make the reasons to stay better than the reasons to leave."
    "(You speak like a scientist and a neighbor; you mean both.)"

    jonah_reyes "And us?"
    "(Simple. Heavy.)"

    maya_armitage "We'll keep doing the work that makes staying possible. We'll keep telling the truth—sometimes loud, sometimes quiet. We'll keep the garden tended and the tide lines taught."
    "(You are honest. You do not promise the fairytale ending you used to draft for sleepless nights.)"

    jonah_reyes "That's enough for now."
    "(He doesn't ask for more. He does not promise forever. He is steady. You are steady. It is its own kind of tenderness.)"
    "There are small rounds of talk after—the repairs to a restoration site, who will care for the elder who can't move, which fund to pursue next. The town is now a network of legal protections and"
    "human arrangements, of enforced oversight that sometimes feels like safety and sometimes like a hand that squeezes too hard. The cost of systemic protection has been measured in shutters nailed permanently and in the grief of"
    "people who had to let homes go."
    "You file your bracelet's data and watch the dots tesselate into curves that mean something: the high nights, the microtemperature spikes, the days of calm. Your perfectionism has been tempered—less a broken thing than a tempered blade that can still cut but no longer seeks impossible precision."
    "You close your hands around the compass and hold your face to the sun. Salt is on your lips by habit now; you taste it the way people taste grief—present, inescapable, codified into memory."
    "A group of children cluster by a whiteboard while you teach them to mark the next tide line. One of them laughs in a way that is surprising for how much meaning it carries. You watch"
    "them and recognize a future that will be neither unmarked loss nor total restoration, but a braided life: laws and gardens, compromises and stubborn acts of care."
    "Gracie Nan appears at the doorway of the lab with a tray of soup; her eyes are the map of the town—wired to its weather, softened by its small economies of love."
    hide rafi_chen
    show gracie_nan_armitage at left:
        zoom 0.7

    gracie_nan_armitage "Come on, you scientist. Eat."
    "(She jabs at you with the spoon the way she jabbed your shoulder in the garden, keeping domestic insistence as a moral strategy.)"
    "You sit. You eat. People talk and repair and count and reckon. The legal scaffolding you helped build is in place; it will not solve everything. It will, however, make some futures legible and defendable. There"
    "are neighborhoods that couldn't be saved, and there are neighborhoods that will remain because people demanded it. There is accountability now—brittle, nascent, sometimes frustrating. It is the shape of progress and the shape of compromise."
    "You rest the compass on the table and let your hand find the bracelet; it blinks once and records this hour. You are resolute: you will keep teaching, keeping repairing, keeping testifying. You are empathetic: you"
    "will continue to hold the stories of the people who were forced to leave. You are aching—still—but you are not alone."
    hide maya_armitage
    hide jonah_reyes
    hide gracie_nan_armitage

    scene bg ch15_228644_4 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Water breathing; distant hammers]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: The cello returns, slow and elegiac, then eases into silence]
    "You stand at the edge of the lab's dock, the compass pointing somewhere you do not name. The harbor returns the town’s dim light in patient ripples. Your shoulders are lighter than last year and heavier than a decade ago. You are proud and tired and quietly grateful."
    "Nan's laugh carries from the garden, small and defiant. Jonah Reyes's voice is a presence that resists neat labels. Rafi jokes about a sensor that finally held through a storm. Kids mark tide lines with too-large handwriting and eyes that will remember to check the sky."
    "You close your palm around the compass; the needle refuses certainty. It knows north, but north will not, on its own, save a town. You know now that salvation is cumulative: small acts, legal scaffolds, gardens,"
    "soup, a few brave filings, and people who keep coming back. You taste salt and something like acceptance—sharp, clean, and real."

